1. Q&A: When you're not trying to checkout a branch, it's standard practice to put -- before the filename. This tells Git to stay on the current branch.

2. Q&A: When you check out a file from a particular revision, it puts that file into your working directory. (false)

3. When you want to completely undo the changes for a commit, you can use the "git revert" command.

4. Q: Suppose you've added a lot of files to your working directory that are not tracked, and you want to get rid of them. Which command would accomplish this the most efficiently?
A: git clean -f
